<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/mmnd.18580020310" author="Kraatz, G" journalOrPublisher="Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="361 - 368" refId="B9" refString="Kraatz, G, 1858. Einige neue und ausgezeichnete Staphylinen-Gattungen. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift 2 (3-4): 361 - 368, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/mmnd.18580020310" title="Einige neue und ausgezeichnete Staphylinen-Gattungen." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/mmnd.18580020310" volume="2" year="1858">Kraatz (1858)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. erythrurus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="erythrurus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. erythrurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on an unknown number of specimens from &quot;Nova Grenada&quot; [= Panama + Colombia]. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" author="Brunke, A" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 113" refId="B2" refString="Brunke, A, Solodovnikov, A, 2014. A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). ZooKeys 423: 1 - 113, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" title="A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" volume="423" year="2014">Brunke and Solodovnikov (2014)</bibRefCitation>
were able to examine one female syntype from the Kraatz collection (SDEI) and redescribed the species based on this and several other, more recently collected single female specimens from medium elevations (1300-1350 m) in southern Puntarenas, Costa Rica and adjacent 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Chiriquí">Chiriqui</normalizedToken>
, Panama. However, the non-syntype females differed from the syntype in coloration, with the former group possessing a bluish forebody and brassy-green elytra (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A-C habitus of Bolitogyrus erythrurus (Kraatz) A non-type, Panama B syntype, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; C non-type, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; D, E pronotum, lateral view D B. viridescens Brunke E B. pseudostrigifrons Brunke F antenna of B. nigropolitoides Brunke. Scale bars: 1 mm (A, B); 0.5 mm (D-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1096.80773.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672695" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1A</figureCitation>
), and the latter a brassy-green forebody and bluish elytra (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A-C habitus of Bolitogyrus erythrurus (Kraatz) A non-type, Panama B syntype, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; C non-type, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; D, E pronotum, lateral view D B. viridescens Brunke E B. pseudostrigifrons Brunke F antenna of B. nigropolitoides Brunke. Scale bars: 1 mm (A, B); 0.5 mm (D-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1096.80773.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672695" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1B</figureCitation>
). The legs of the syntype also appeared darker and less clearly bicolored than the non-syntypes and most species of the genus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A-C habitus of Bolitogyrus erythrurus (Kraatz) A non-type, Panama B syntype, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; C non-type, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; D, E pronotum, lateral view D B. viridescens Brunke E B. pseudostrigifrons Brunke F antenna of B. nigropolitoides Brunke. Scale bars: 1 mm (A, B); 0.5 mm (D-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1096.80773.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672695" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1B</figureCitation>
), though this was thought to be due to age or discoloration from a killing agent (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" author="Brunke, A" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 113" refId="B2" refString="Brunke, A, Solodovnikov, A, 2014. A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). ZooKeys 423: 1 - 113, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" title="A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" volume="423" year="2014">Brunke and Solodovnikov 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The above specimen from IRSNB (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A-C habitus of Bolitogyrus erythrurus (Kraatz) A non-type, Panama B syntype, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; C non-type, &quot; Nova Grenada &quot; D, E pronotum, lateral view D B. viridescens Brunke E B. pseudostrigifrons Brunke F antenna of B. nigropolitoides Brunke. Scale bars: 1 mm (A, B); 0.5 mm (D-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1096.80773.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672695" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1C</figureCitation>
), also collected from &quot;Nova Grenada&quot;, corresponds closely with the syntype in coloration, including the faintly but clearly bicolored legs with a paler area in the basal third of the femur. This raises the possibility that 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. erythrurus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="erythrurus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. erythrurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described from present-day Colombia rather than Panama and may not be conspecific with the specimens previously examined from Central America. This hypothesis is further supported by an image taken by D. Hoyos Velasquez of a live specimen from La Tebaida, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Quindío">Quindio</normalizedToken>
, Colombia (mid-elevation, northern Andes), matching the coloration of specimens from &quot;Nova Grenada&quot; and posted on various social media websites (e.g., https://www.facebook.com/groups/491915904153407/posts/2464208683590776). This image represents the first definitive evidence of the Buphthalmus group in South America. A more accurate species concept for 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. erythrurus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="erythrurus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. erythrurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is badly needed but will not be possible without the study of male specimens from both Central and South America.
</paragraph>
